wrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uedeina.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Edeina</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Board Mistress</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/8/01 2:44:31 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> About languages</span><hr size=1> I was about to reply to the &quot;shafted in PoF&quot; thread, but since my reply had nothing to do with the original subject I decided to start a new thread instead.<br>
<br>
So, about americans getting upset when people speak german...<br>
In my eyes it's not so much that americans speak only english while germans speak both german and english.<br>
<br>
It's more that germans often know english and german, but not french and swedish, while swedes often know swedish and english, but not german and french, and so on.<br>
<br>
As always, it's a matter of balance.<br>
Demanding that english be spoken at all times is pure silliness. <br>
On the other hand, spamming people with text they can't understand or cutting them out of the talk by using a unknown language, that's really rude.<br>
<br>
I am from sweden, yet I am among those who have at times complained about people speaking french or german in situations or extents I found inappropriate. Most of those times someone replied to me that we americans should shut our mouths. Hey, I'm no fanatic about english, it's not even my language. It just happens to be a language that I can speak!<br>
<br>
So, where goes the line then?<br>
In my eyes, people raiding or visiting zones that are otherwise more or less empty should use whatever language that suits them. Ibn more packed zones, none-english should be limited to greetings and very short conversations. Those zones are spammed enough as it is, without the added preassure of text that is simply &quot;fhsdlfhs fsidfhsrif f sdifpsudf fsodpfjurswef&quot; to most readers. <br>
<br>
Also, if all six in a group understands one language but five are more comfortable with a language the sixth don't understand, then stick to the first language goddamnit.<br>
<br>
I have many times been in groups with five swedes and one german. We used english at all times since we all know that language while the germans (one german each time, but different germans in different groups) didn't know swedish and several swedes didn't know german. Of course we five could have talked swedish with each other instead, but cutting out the german guy from the grouptalk wouldn't be nice, would it?<br>
Yet that have happened to me so many times when grouped with germans or frenshmen that insisted that it's my own problem if I don't know their language.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p>Love, Edeina<br>
Highelf Conjurer of Erollisi<br>
Ayonae Ro Server<br>
<a href="http://Ayonae.Ro">Ayonae.Ro</a> Server Community Board</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ubraxcodh.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BraxCoDH</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/8/01 2:58:09 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.culdi.de/Mitglieder/Brax/brax_small.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: About languages</span><hr size=1> About /ooc /shout or /aution you are right. English should be the normal language if there are people in the zone that dont know your native language.<br>
<br>
Grouptalk is a litte bit different. I know three people - two from my guild - that speak nerly no english. I often get /t or /gu like &quot;what does (english text) mean&quot; or &quot;how do i say (german text) in english&quot;. What if we are a group of 5 people who speak german and than someone enters who didnt speak german ? <br>
<br>
But in all other cases i agree with you.<br>
<br>
