Ayonae Ro</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ustrikefear.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Strike Fear</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/8/01 3:06:53 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: About languages</span><hr size=1> Lol, I've run into this myself and when I do run into these situations where there it's a matter of just being rude by the germans, sedish, or whatever... I keep my mouth shut and after a few requests to keep the conversation to tells being ignored I switch to words that everyone can understand and make my exit from the group.  All players of all languages I believe know the word, Train!<br>
<br>
An argument can be made that the game is an American produced game and the default language should be English.  If I were playing a Japanese produced game I would expect the default language to be Japanese. A French produced game... defult language I would expect to be, of course, French.  To the person of which you speak that was saying that Americans should just keep their mouths shut I would have to respond by saying, &quot;Get the fuck off our internet before we decide to do some policing actions in your part of the world.  Now shut the fuck up before we cut your supply of Pepsi and Coke.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now, being an American who speaks only a tiddle of French as a second language... I'm trying to improve a bit.  I will have to admit that some languages to me right now are an f'n mystery I'm not willing to touch just yet.  Those languages being Japanese, Swedish, and Dutch.  I am making some efforts to learn German and more French as I see myself having to dealing with more and more languages in the future.  I'm not going to stop playing online games and I'm going to have to deal with more and more folks of other nations with different languages.  Besides, it never hurts to improve yourself.  My only wish is that I had run into all these people years ago when I would have had the time and the real desire to learn those extra languages.<br>
<br>
<br>
Strike Fear<br>
Arch Lich<br>
Undead Lords<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ufebreeza.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Febreeza</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/8/01 4:10:11 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.facelink.com/Febreeza?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: About languages</span><hr size=1> If you think about this in the EQ sense it is very much like your character, let's say you are an Ogre, being grouped with 4 other Ogres and a Gnome.  If the Ogres all speak Ogre, the Gnome doesnt necessarily know what is going on, besides this being rude.  That is why the game has a COMMON language.<br>
<br>
In this instance we can think of English as being the 'common' language of the game.  I don't mind occassionally seeing /ooc, /shout, /auction in another language but when it continues over time, I will send one of the people a tell asking them to take it to tells.  It becomes annoying trying to see what is going on in zone and not being able to read half of it.  Or having it look like gibberish.  I too have many friends in many different countries.  I do not speak other languages, but since I have not had alot of interaction in the past with people who speak other languages, I will not apologize for it.  <br>
<br>
Lord knows America has enough differences in its own language as well as Canadians.  Going from one part of this country or into Canada can be very much like going from one country to another in Europe.  You learn the most common terms in the country (or part of the country) that you go into often.  If we are not going into France, Sweden, Germany, or any other part of Europe, why should we learn your language?  In this game we are not visiting your country, you are visiting ours.  It is polite to use the language of the country you are in.<br>
<br>
Where Latin used to be the world common language.  It seems that English has become the world common language.  If you are playing a world common game, it is just polite to use the common language.  In this instance it is English. If another language takes over as world common, then we should all learn it.  Until then it is rude to continue to speak in another language after being &quot;politely&quot; asked to take it somewhere else.  And I assure you I have always asked politely.<br>
<br>
I am ashamed at some of the things I have seen Americans say to Europeans in shouts and, in tells, take them to task even more than the Europeans.  I have found that the /ignore works just as good to stop having to read stuff that bothers me.  And I use it liberally.<br>
<br>
Just my 2 cp <p><b><i><h5>Febreeza Tinytank</i></b><br>
<b><i>Level 45 Warrioress - Ayonae Ro</i></b><BR>
<b><i>Level 13 Warrioress - Sol Ro</i></b><BR>
<BR>
<b><i>Mischievous Nonnsense</i></b><BR>
<b><i>Level 23 Rogue - Ayonae Ro</h5></i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uedeina.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Edeina</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Board Mistress</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/8/01 4:12:14 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: About languages</span><hr size=1> If six people do not have one common language, then they will have a hard time grouping with each other. If they do they will have to work it out somehow, perhaps with a groupmember or two that know both languages working as a translator.<br>
<br>
I have been in one such group. It was ok. They warned me about the language problem before I joined, and then we communicated as well as we could.<br>
<br>
But if I join a group and my five groupmates all keep to german (or frensh or japanese or whatever), then there are only two explenations. Either none of them have a common language with me, and in that case I should not be in the group and it was wrong of them to invite me without warning. Or they simply choose to treat me badly because I am not of teh same nationality as they are.<br>
